Build heap in linear time.

If you already have an array of values and want to build a heap from them, inserting one at a time takes n log n time. There is a smarter approach: start from the last non-leaf node — which is at index n divided by two, minus one — and apply sift-down to every node from there back to the root.

The key insight is that nodes near the leaves are the majority of the tree, and they require very little work — most need zero or one swaps. The total work across all nodes sums to linear time. This is why Python's heapify function, which converts a list into a heap in place, runs in linear time rather than n log n.
